elevated white cell count. A CT scan is performed (Image 1, 2).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Splenic haematoma","Subphrenic abscess","Splenic abscess","Splenic infarction","Pancreatitis"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe CT scan shows a multiloculated fluid collection in the mid-body of the spleen, extending towards the hilum (Image). Whilst the changes in the spleen could be due to haematoma formation, there is no history of trauma and the history of a fever and intravenous drug use point strongly to an infectious aetiology. The pancreas appears normal and there is no fluid collection outside the spleen. These findings, together with the clinical picture are consistent with a \u003Cstrong\u003Esplenic abscess\u003C/strong\u003E. Splenic abscess formation is an uncommon clinical entity and one with a high mortality if not recognised. The source of infection is often haematogenous, or it can be contiguous, with spread from infected adjacent organs or tissue spaces. Infective endocarditis is probably the commonest source of infection.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A splenic abscess is usually result of seeding from haematogenous spread."],"references":["Lee M-C, Lee C-M, Splenic Abscess: An Uncommon Entity with Potentially Life-Threatening Evolution. Can J Infect Dis Med Microbiol. 2018:8610657."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56076"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"812"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"15327"},{"type":"media","id":"15328"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20398"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"15327","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/15327"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/4765f1ce-f2c3-40b9-83d9-8518244d570a.jpg","thu